LEGIONELLOSIS - NEW ZEALAND: (CANTERBURY) COMPOST, POTTING SOIL
***************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: Sun 7 Oct 2018
Source: Stuff [edited]
https://www.stuff.co.nz/the-press/107654679/Legionnaires-survivor-worked-for-compost-company-wants-to-warn-others-of-danger


Driving compost around was what likely led to one man being declared the sickest person in New Zealand. [A 41-year-old man] had just started a new job at a gardening supplies company when he was struck down by legionnaires' disease.

The Christchurch man became unwell with cold and flu-like symptoms on 16 Sep 2018, but 4 days later, he was put into an induced coma in Christchurch Hospital intensive care unit (ICU). He was moved out of the ICU to a general ward on Friday [5 Oct 2018] after 12 days on life support.

The father of 2 boys spent 2.5 years unable to work due to a back injury and recovery from 2 major surgeries. He had re-trained and obtained truck-driving licenses in an effort to change careers. At the end of August 2018, he was thrilled to start a new job transporting compost and gardening soil, [his] sister said. But his new start came to an abrupt end 3 weeks later.

What started as a regular cough and cold accelerated into a life-threatening respiratory disease within hours, [his sister] said. "Because the symptoms are just like the flu, you don't know how sick you are until it's life or death." On 21 Sep 2018, staff put him into an induced coma when he was struggling to breathe. The father of 2 was treated with general antibiotics for the 1st few days until a diagnosis of legionnaires' [disease] was made on 25 Sep 2018. Treatment with legionnaires' [disease] specific antibiotics worked to attack the _Legionella_ bacteria. Over several days, he was brought out of a coma.

Doctors believed it was most likely he had contracted the disease from inhalation of the legionellosis bacteria in the compost and gardening mix he was transporting for his job, his sister said.

[Byline: Cate Broughton]

