******
[2]
Date: Fri 5 Oct 2018
Source: Stuff [edited]
https://www.stuff.co.nz/national/health/107643813/person-in-intensive-care-with-legionnaires-disease-in-christchurch?rm=m


A Canterbury man spent about 2 weeks in intensive care after falling ill with legionnaires' disease.

Canterbury medical officer of health Dr Alistair Humphrey said the man, aged under 45 [years], was diagnosed "a couple of weeks ago" due to compost exposure. The man was released from intensive care on Friday [5 Oct 2018], but further details on his condition were not available.

Humphrey said several others had been admitted to hospital with the disease this year [2018] but did not require intensive care. He did not know how many.

Last year [2017], 62 Cantabrians were hospitalised with legionnaires', and 13 required intensive care. One patient was admitted to intensive care for 42 days.

Canterbury medical officer of health Dr Alistair Humphrey says gardeners have a higher risk of catching legionnaires' disease. In November last year [2017], 24 Cantabrians were diagnosed with the disease, the highest monthly number ever recorded. Humphrey said Cantabrians needed to take care with potting mix and compost to avoid repeating last year's spike.

"Legionnaires' tends to grow quite well in warm conditions. We've had a warm winter and are expecting a warm summer," he said. "Last year [2017], we had a record number, and this year we are expecting it to be warmer than last year."

Humphrey said there were 5 key actions gardeners could take to avoid the disease: opening potting mix carefully, wearing a safety mask when gardening, dampening down potting mix with compost or water, working with potting mix in a well-ventilated area, and washing hands thoroughly. Life-sized cutouts of Humphrey were in garden centres around the region with warning pamphlets, as had been done for the last few years. Humphrey said there were also warning signs on packets of gardening mix.

Legionnaires' is a type of pneumonia. The illness may be mild but can be fatal. It is more common in older people, especially if they smoke, have poor immunity, or have a chronic illness. Symptoms include dry coughing, high fever, chills, diarrhoea, shortness of breath, chest pains, headaches, excessive sweating, nausea, vomiting, and abdominal pain.

[Byline: Tom Kitchin]

